The participants of inter-Afghan negotiations held here on May 28-30 have failed to reach a ceasefire agreement, TASS news agency reported Thursday. "There is only a statement saying that the ceasefire talks will continue," TASS quoted former Governor of Afghanistan's Balkh Province Atta Mohammad Noor as saying. According to the statement cited by TASS, the participants discussed the continuation of intra-Afghan talks, a ceasefire, saving people's lives, the problem of prisoners and the withdrawal of foreign armed forces from Afghanistan. They also discussed the consolidation of Islamic forces, the preservation of national unity and territorial integrity, as well as the rights of women. Chinese scientists design gene-editing tool using light to kill cancer cellsAbsence at PLA maritime parade will prevent US from learning about Chinese Navy: expertsChinese American organization condemns increasing racial profiling in US Contribution rememberedChild porn arrests shock S.California Chinese communityUtah celebrates 150th birthday of Transcontinental Railroad